# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: keydb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] Go directly to github to see source code, create issues/PRs, or if you like the project give it a star or follow us!
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] A place to see te latest announcements and news related to everything KeyDB.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] KeyDB is meant to handle heavy workloads with a single node benchmarking at over 1 million ops/sec.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] KeyDB is a multithreaded database and will outperform Redis on a per-node basis.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] By keeping data in-memory, KeyDB can serve up data with submillisecond latencies.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] Periodically dump the dataset to disk or by appending each command to a disk-based log.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] While a single KeyDB node scales vertically, you can scale horizonally through active-replication, or cluster-mode (sharded dataset) to meet much larger workloads.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] High availability setups are simple with active-replica nodes that do not require sentinel nodes for failover.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] With an MVCC implementation at the underlying architecture, KeyDB can query individual snapshots of the database, avoiding otherwise blocking calls such as SCAN and KEYS.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] Run multiple master nodes replicated asynchronously to eachother with a last write wins methodology.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] This enables support of a single replicated dataset where all nodes are masters with no need for sentinel monitoring nodes for failover.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] KeyDB offers Subkey EXPIREs which enables expiration of members within a set.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] EXPIREs now also have near real time active deletion that removes major lags associated with old models of removing expired keys.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] KeyDB offers TLS support that can operate at 7x the throughput of Redis + TLS While TLS encryption adds additional CPU overhead, KeyDB’s multithreaded architecture enables more worker threads to prevent any decline in performance.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] Create your own commands with KeyDB’s open source javascript module.
[src:keydb/docs-keydb-dev] **FLASH storage** is scheduled for release in Q3, we are also working on **JSON support, multi-tenant support, and RAFT**.
[src:keydb/download] KeyDB offers a variety of packages for easy installation accross different distributions and architectures.
[src:keydb/download] The packages and distribution methods outlined below are actively managed by KeyDB.
[src:keydb/download] The KeyDB Community has created and is managing some great distribution channels!
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:keydb/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] A **key-value database**, or **key-value store**, is a data storage paradigm designed for storing, retrieving, and managing associative arrays, a data structure more commonly known today as a *dictionary*.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] Dictionaries contain a collection of *objects*, or *records*, which in turn have many different *fields* within them.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] These records are stored and retrieved using a *key* that uniquely identifies the record, and is used to find the data within the database.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] Key-value databases differ from the better known relational databases (RDB).
[src:keydb/key-value-database] RDBs pre-define the data structure in the database as a series of tables containing fields with well-defined data types.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] Exposing the data types to the database program allows it to apply various optimizations.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] In contrast, key-value systems treat the value as opaque to the database itself, and typically support only simple operations such as storing, retrieving, updating, and deleting a value by its key.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] This offers considerable flexibility and makes such systems well suited to low-latency, high-throughput workloads dominated by direct key lookups, but less suitable for applications that require complex queries or explicit relationships among records.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] A lack of standardization, limited transaction support, and relatively simple query interfaces long restricted many key-value systems to specialized uses, but the rapid move to cloud computing after 2010 helped drive renewed interest in them as part of the broader NoSQL movement.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] Some graph databases, such as ArangoDB, are also key–value databases internally, adding the concept of relationships (*pointers*) between records as a first-class data type.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] Key–value systems span a wide consistency spectrum, from eventually consistent designs to strongly consistent or serializable ones, and some allow the consistency level to be configured as part of the trade-off against latency and availability.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] Renewed interest in key–value and other NoSQL systems was driven in part by the demands of big data, distributed, and cloud applications.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] Their scalability and availability made them attractive for cloud data management, although limited transaction support, low-level query interfaces, and the lack of standardization remained obstacles to wider adoption.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] Some maintain data in memory (RAM), while others employ solid-state drives or rotating disks.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] Some key–value systems add additional structure to their keys.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] For example, Oracle NoSQL Database organizes records using composite keys with "major" and "minor" components, an arrangement that Oracle compares to a directory-path structure in a file system.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] More generally, however, key–value stores are defined by their use of unique keys associated with opaque values and by their emphasis on simple key-based operations.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] Unix included *dbm* (database manager), a minimal database library written by Ken Thompson for managing associative arrays with a single key and hash-based access.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] Later implementations and related libraries included sdbm, GNU dbm (gdbm), and Berkeley DB.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] A more recent example is RocksDB, a persistent key–value storage engine developed at Facebook and designed for large-scale applications.
[src:keydb/key-value-database] Other examples include in-memory systems such as Memcached and Redis, and persistent systems such as Berkeley DB, Riak, and Voldemort.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB is a high performance fork of Redis with a focus on multithreading, memory efficiency, and high throughput.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] In addition to performance improvements, KeyDB offers features such as Active Replication, FLASH Storage and Subkey Expires.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB has a MVCC architecture that allows you to execute queries such as KEYS and SCAN without blocking the database and degrading performance.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB maintains full compatibility with the Redis protocol, modules, and scripts.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] This includes the atomicity guarantees for scripts and transactions.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Because KeyDB keeps in sync with Redis development KeyDB is a superset of Redis functionality, making KeyDB a drop in replacement for existing Redis deployments.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] On the same hardware KeyDB can achieve significantly higher throughput than Redis.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Active-Replication simplifies hot-spare failover allowing you to easily distribute writes over replicas and use simple TCP based load balancing/failover.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB's higher performance allows you to do more on less hardware which reduces operation costs and complexity.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] The chart below compares several KeyDB and Redis setups, including the latest Redis6 io-threads option, and TLS benchmarks.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB has a different philosophy on how the codebase should evolve.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] We feel that ease of use, high performance, and a "batteries included" approach is the best way to create a good user experience.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] While we have great respect for the Redis maintainers it is our opinion that the Redis approach focuses too much on simplicity of the code base at the expense of complexity for the user.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] This results in the need for external components and workarounds to solve common problems - resulting in more complexity overall.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Because of this difference of opinion features which are right for KeyDB may not be appropriate for Redis.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] A fork allows us to explore this new development path and implement features which may never be a part of Redis.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB keeps in sync with upstream Redis changes, and where applicable we upstream bug fixes and changes.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] It is our hope that the two projects can continue to grow and learn from each other.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] The KeyDB team maintains this project as part of Snap Inc.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB is used by Snap as part of its caching infrastructure and is fully open sourced.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] There is no separate commercial product and no paid support options available.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] We really value collaborating with the open source community and welcome PRs, bug reports, and open discussion.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] For community support or to get involved further with the project check out our community support options here (slack, forum, meetup, github issues).
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Our team monitors these channels regularly.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Please note keydb-benchmark and redis-benchmark are currently single threaded and too slow to properly benchmark KeyDB.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] We recommend using a redis cluster benchmark tool such as memtier.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Please ensure your machine has enough cores for both KeyDB and memtier if testing locally.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB expects exclusive use of any cores assigned to it.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] All other configuration options behave as you'd expect.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Your existing configuration files should continue to work unchanged.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] The number of threads used to serve requests.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] This should be related to the number of queues available in your network hardware, *not* the number of cores on your machine.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Because KeyDB uses spinlocks to reduce latency; making this too high will reduce performance.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] The minimum number of clients on a thread before KeyDB assigns new connections to a different thread.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB will attempt to balance clients across threads evenly; However, replica clients are usually much more expensive than a normal client, and so KeyDB will try to assign fewer clients to threads with a replica.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] The weighting factor below is intended to help tune this behavior.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] A replica weighting factor of 2 means we treat a replica as the equivalent of two normal clients.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Adjusting this value may improve performance when replication is used.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] The best weighting is workload specific - e.g. read heavy workloads should set this to 1.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Very write heavy workloads may benefit from higher numbers.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Should KeyDB make active attempts at balancing clients across threads?
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] This can impact performance accepting new clients.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] If disabled there is still a best effort from the kernel to distribute across threads with SO_REUSEPORT but it will not be as fair.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] If you are using active-active replication set `active-replica` option to “yes”.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] This will enable both instances to accept reads and writes while remaining synced.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Click here to see more on active-rep in our docs section.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Avoid forwarding RREPLAY messages to other masters?
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] You must be certain all masters are connected to eachother in a true mesh topology or data loss will occur!
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] If you would like KeyDB to dump and load directly to AWS S3 this option specifies the bucket.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Using this option with the traditional RDB options will result in KeyDB backing up twice to both locations.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] If both are specified KeyDB will first attempt to load from the local dump file and if that fails load from S3.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] This requires the AWS CLI tools to be installed and configured which are used under the hood to transfer the data.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] If you would like to use KeyDB FLASH storage, specify the storage medium followed by the directory path on your local SSD volume.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Note that this feature is still considered experimental and should be used with discretion.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] See FLASH Documentation for more details on configuration and setting up your FLASH volume.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB can be compiled and is tested for use on Linux.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB currently relies on SO_REUSEPORT's load balancing behavior which is available only in Linux.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] When we support marshalling connections across threads we plan to support other operating systems such as FreeBSD.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB by default is built with TLS enabled.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB has some dependencies which are included in the `deps` directory.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] `make` does not automatically rebuild dependencies even if something in the source code of dependencies changes.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] This will clean: jemalloc, lua, hiredis, linenoise.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Also if you force certain build options like 32bit target, no C compiler optimizations (for debugging purposes), and other similar build time options, those options are cached indefinitely until you issue a `make distclean` command.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] If after building KeyDB with a 32 bit target you need to rebuild it with a 64 bit target, or the other way around, you need to perform a `make distclean` in the root directory of the KeyDB distribution.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Selecting a non-default memory allocator when building KeyDB is done by setting the `MALLOC` environment variable.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB is compiled and linked against libc malloc by default, with the exception of jemalloc being the default on Linux systems.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] This default was picked because jemalloc has proven to have fewer fragmentation problems than libc malloc.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] By default, KeyDB will build using the POSIX clock_gettime function as the monotonic clock source.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] On most modern systems, the internal processor clock can be used to improve performance.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB will build with a user friendly colorized output by default.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] It is possible to alter the KeyDB configuration by passing parameters directly as options using the command line.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] All the options in keydb.conf are also supported as options using the command line, with exactly the same name.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Please consult the TLS.md file for more information on how to use KeyDB with TLS.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] You can use keydb-cli to play with KeyDB.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] You can use `make PREFIX=/some/other/directory install` if you wish to use a different destination.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Make install will just install binaries in your system, but will not configure init scripts and configuration files in the appropriate place.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] The script will ask you a few questions and will setup everything you need to run KeyDB properly as a background daemon that will start again on system reboots.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] You'll be able to stop and start KeyDB using the script named `/etc/init.d/keydb_<portnumber>`, for instance `/etc/init.d/keydb_6379`.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] KeyDB works by running the normal Redis event loop on multiple threads.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Network IO, and query parsing are done concurrently.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Each connection is assigned a thread on accept().
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Access to the core hash table is guarded by spinlock.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Because the hashtable access is extremely fast this lock has low contention.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Transactions hold the lock for the duration of the EXEC command.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Modules work in concert with the GIL which is only acquired when all server threads are paused.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] This maintains the atomicity guarantees modules expect.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Unlike most databases the core data structure is the fastest part of the system.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Most of the query time comes from parsing the REPL protocol and copying data to/from the network.
[src:keydb/main-readme-md] Please see the CONTRIBUTING file in this source distribution for more information.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] In computer architecture, **multithreading** is the ability of a central processing unit (CPU) (or a single core in a multi-core processor) to provide multiple threads of execution.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] The multithreading paradigm has become more popular as efforts to further exploit instruction-level parallelism have stalled since the late 1990s.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] This allowed the concept of throughput computing to re-emerge from the more specialized field of transaction processing.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Even though it is very difficult to further speed up a single thread or single program, most computer systems are actually multitasking among multiple threads or programs.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Thus, techniques that improve the throughput of all tasks result in overall performance gains.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Two major techniques for throughput computing are *multithreading* and *multiprocessing*.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] If a thread gets a lot of cache misses, the other threads can continue taking advantage of the unused computing resources, which may lead to faster overall execution, as these resources would have been idle if only a single thread were executed.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Also, if a thread cannot use all the computing resources of the CPU (because instructions depend on each other's results), running another thread may prevent those resources from becoming idle.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Multiple threads can interfere with each other when sharing hardware resources such as caches or translation lookaside buffers (TLBs).
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] As a result, execution times of a single thread are not improved and can be degraded, even when only one thread is executing, due to lower frequencies or additional pipeline stages that are necessary to accommodate thread-switching hardware.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Overall efficiency varies; Intel claims up to 30% improvement with its Hyper-Threading Technology, while a synthetic program just performing a loop of non-optimized dependent floating-point operations actually gains a 100% speed improvement when run in parallel.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] On the other hand, hand-tuned assembly language programs using MMX or AltiVec extensions and performing data prefetches (as a good video encoder might) do not suffer from cache misses or idle computing resources.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Such programs therefore do not benefit from hardware multithreading and can indeed see degraded performance due to contention for shared resources.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] From the software standpoint, hardware support for multithreading is more visible to software, requiring more changes to both application programs and operating systems than multiprocessing.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Hardware techniques used to support multithreading often parallel the software techniques used for computer multitasking.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Thread scheduling is also a major problem in multithreading.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Merging data from two processes can often incur significantly higher costs compared to processing the same data on a single thread, potentially by two or more orders of magnitude due to overheads such as inter-process communication and synchronization.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] The simplest type of multithreading occurs when one thread runs until it is blocked by an event that normally would create a long-latency stall.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Such a stall might be a cache miss that has to access off-chip memory, which might take hundreds of CPU cycles for the data to return.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Instead of waiting for the stall to resolve, a threaded processor would switch execution to another thread that was ready to run.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Only when the data for the previous thread had arrived, would the previous thread be placed back on the list of ready-to-run threads.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Cycle *i* + 1: instruction *j* + 1 from thread A is issued.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Cycle *i* + 2: instruction *j* + 2 from thread A is issued, which is a load instruction that misses in all caches.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Cycle *i* + 3: thread scheduler invoked, switches to thread B.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Cycle *i* + 4: instruction k from thread B is issued.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Cycle *i* + 5: instruction *k* + 1 from thread B is issued.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Conceptually, it is similar to cooperative multi-tasking used in real-time operating systems, in which tasks voluntarily give up execution time when they need to wait upon some type of event.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] This type of multithreading is known as block, cooperative or coarse-grained multithreading.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] The goal of multithreading hardware support is to allow quick switching between a blocked thread and another thread ready to run.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Switching from one thread to another means the hardware switches from using one register set to another.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] To achieve this goal, the hardware for the program visible registers, as well as some processor control registers (such as the program counter), is replicated.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] For example, to quickly switch between two threads, the processor is built with two sets of registers.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Additional hardware support for multithreading allows thread switching to be done in one CPU cycle, bringing performance improvements.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Also, additional hardware allows each thread to behave as if it were executing alone and not sharing any hardware resources with other threads, minimizing the amount of software changes needed within the application and the operating system to support multithreading.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Many families of microcontrollers and embedded processors have multiple register banks to allow quick context switching for interrupts.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Such schemes can be considered a type of block multithreading among the user program thread and the interrupt threads.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] The purpose of fine-grained multithreading is to remove all data dependency stalls from the execution pipeline.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Since one thread is relatively independent from other threads, there is less chance of one instruction in one pipelining stage needing an output from an older instruction in the pipeline.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Conceptually, it is similar to preemptive multitasking used in operating systems; an analogy would be that the time slice given to each active thread is one CPU cycle.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Cycle *i* + 2: an instruction from thread C is issued.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] This type of multithreading was first called barrel processing, in which the staves of a barrel represent the pipeline stages and their executing threads.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Interleaved, preemptive, fine-grained or time-sliced multithreading are more modern terminology.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] In addition to the hardware costs discussed in the block type of multithreading, interleaved multithreading has an additional cost of each pipeline stage tracking the thread ID of the instruction it is processing.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Also, since there are more threads being executed concurrently in the pipeline, shared resources such as caches and TLBs need to be larger to avoid thrashing between the different threads.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] The most advanced type of multithreading applies to superscalar processors.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Whereas a normal superscalar processor issues multiple instructions from a single thread every CPU cycle, in simultaneous multithreading (SMT) a superscalar processor can issue instructions from multiple threads every CPU cycle.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Recognizing that any single thread has a limited amount of instruction-level parallelism, this type of multithreading tries to exploit parallelism available across multiple threads to decrease the waste associated with unused issue slots.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Cycle *i* + 1: instruction *j* + 2 from thread A, instruction *k* + 1 from thread B, and instruction m from thread C are all simultaneously issued.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Cycle *i* + 2: instruction *j* + 3 from thread A and instructions *m* + 1 and *m* + 2 from thread C are all simultaneously issued.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] To distinguish the other types of multithreading from SMT, the term "temporal multithreading" is used to denote when instructions from only one thread can be issued at a time.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] In addition to the hardware costs discussed for interleaved multithreading, SMT has the additional cost of each pipeline stage tracking the thread ID of each instruction being processed.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Again, shared resources such as caches and TLBs have to be sized for the large number of active threads being processed.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Implementations include DEC (later Compaq) EV8 (not completed), Intel Hyper-Threading Technology, IBM POWER5/POWER6/POWER7/POWER8/POWER9, IBM z13/z14/z15, Sun Microsystems UltraSPARC T2, Cray XMT, and AMD Bulldozer and Zen microarchitectures.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] A major area of research is the thread scheduler that must quickly choose from among the list of ready-to-run threads to execute next, as well as maintain the ready-to-run and stalled thread lists.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] An important subtopic is the different thread priority schemes that can be used by the scheduler.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] The thread scheduler might be implemented totally in software, totally in hardware, or as a hardware/software combination.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] Another area of research is what type of events should cause a thread switch: cache misses, inter-thread communication, DMA completion, etc.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] If the multithreading scheme replicates all of the software-visible state, including privileged control registers and TLBs, then it enables virtual machines to be created for each thread.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] This allows each thread to run its own operating system on the same processor.
[src:keydb/multithreading-computer-architecture] On the other hand, if only user-mode state is saved, then less hardware is required, which would allow more threads to be active at one time for the same die area or cost.
[src:keydb/redis] The project was developed and maintained by Salvatore Sanfilippo, starting in 2009.
[src:keydb/redis] From 2015 until 2020, he led a project core team sponsored by Redis Labs.
[src:keydb/redis] Salvatore Sanfilippo left Redis as the maintainer in 2020.
[src:keydb/redis] In 2021 Redis Labs dropped the Labs from its name and now is known simply as "Redis".
[src:keydb/redis] In 2018, some modules for Redis adopted a modified Apache 2.0 license with a Commons Clause.
[src:keydb/redis] In 2024, the main Redis code switched from the open-source BSD-3 license to being dual-licensed under the Redis Source Available License v2 and the Server Side Public License v1.
[src:keydb/redis] On May 1, 2025, Redis became tri-licensed beginning with version 8.0, with the GNU Affero General Public License as the third option.
[src:keydb/redis] The name *Redis* means Remote Dictionary Server.
[src:keydb/redis] The Redis project began when Salvatore Sanfilippo (nicknamed *antirez*) was trying to improve the scalability of his Italian startup and developed a real-time web log analyzer.
[src:keydb/redis] After encountering significant problems in scaling some types of workloads using traditional database systems, Sanfilippo began in 2009 to prototype a first proof of concept version of Redis in Tcl.
[src:keydb/redis] Later, Sanfilippo translated that prototype to the C language and implemented the first data type, the list.
[src:keydb/redis] After a few weeks of using the project internally with success, Sanfilippo decided to open source it, announcing the project on Hacker News.
[src:keydb/redis] The project began to get traction, particularly among the Ruby community, with GitHub and Instagram being among the first companies adopting it.
[src:keydb/redis] Sanfilippo was hired by VMware in March 2010.
[src:keydb/redis] In May 2013, Redis was sponsored by Pivotal Software (a VMware spin-off).
[src:keydb/redis] In June 2015, development became sponsored by Redis Ltd.
[src:keydb/redis] This made the modules source-available and no longer free software.
[src:keydb/redis] The core Redis software remained under a BSD license, with Redis Ltd. committing to maintaining these terms.
[src:keydb/redis] In October 2018, Redis 5.0 was released, introducing Redis Stream – a new data structure that allows storage of multiple fields and string values with an automatic, time-based sequence at a single key.
[src:keydb/redis] In June 2020, Salvatore Sanfilippo stepped down as Redis' sole maintainer.
[src:keydb/redis] Sanfilippo was succeeded by Yossi Gottlieb and Oran Agra.
[src:keydb/redis] In March 2024, Redis Ltd. announced that beginning with version 7.4, the core Redis software would be relicensed under the RSAL and Server Side Public License (SSPL), both of which are source-available and non-free.
[src:keydb/redis] The Linux Foundation subsequently announced that it would fork the last BSD-licensed version of Redis as Valkey.
[src:keydb/redis] In May 2025, Redis Ltd. announced that it would change the license again to the AGPL beginning on version 8.0, citing that forks had achieved their goal of creating a "level playing field" of differentiated products, and that Redis has achieved "record growth" since the change in license.
[src:keydb/redis] Sanfilippo returned to Redis in December 2024.
[src:keydb/redis] Redis is a system that functions as both a data store and a cache.
[src:keydb/redis] Data is modified and read from the main computer memory while also being persisted to disk in a format optimized for sequential access rather than random access.
[src:keydb/redis] The formatted data is only reconstructed into memory once the system restarts.
[src:keydb/redis] Redis uses a data model that differs from relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:keydb/redis] Commands specify operations on abstract data types rather than queries to be executed by a database engine.
[src:keydb/redis] Data is stored in structures designed for direct retrieval.
[src:keydb/redis] It does not rely on secondary indexes, aggregations, or other features common in traditional RDBMS.
[src:keydb/redis] The Redis implementation uses the fork system call to duplicate the process holding the data.
[src:keydb/redis] This allows the parent process to continue serving clients while the child process persists the in-memory data to disk.
[src:keydb/redis] Redis supports a number of data types including Strings, JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) documents, Hashes (a collection of fields, each field is a name-value string pair), lists, sets, vector sets, and more.
[src:keydb/redis] The Redis Query Engine allows users to use Redis as a document database, a vector database, a secondary index, and a search engine.
[src:keydb/redis] With Redis Query Engine, users can define indexes for hash and JSON documents, and use a rich query language for vector search, full-text search, geospatial queries, and aggregations.
[src:keydb/redis] Redis Pub/Sub (short for publish/subscribe) is a lightweight messaging capability.
[src:keydb/redis] Publishers send messages to a channel, and subscribers receive messages from that channel.
[src:keydb/redis] A Redis transaction allows the execution of a group of commands in a single step.
[src:keydb/redis] A request sent by another client will never be served during the execution of a transaction.
[src:keydb/redis] This guarantees that the commands are executed as a single isolated operation.
[src:keydb/redis] Redis users can also upload and execute Lua scripts on the server.
[src:keydb/redis] As of May 1, 2025, for all version of Redis starting with 8.0, all data types are included in the same package and available under the Redis Source Available license v2.
[src:keydb/redis] Previously some data types were separate and therefore available under difference licenses.
[src:keydb/redis] Redis typically holds the whole dataset in memory.
[src:keydb/redis] Versions up to 2.4 could be configured to use what they refer to as virtual memory in which some of the dataset is stored on disk, but this feature is deprecated.
[src:keydb/redis] Redis can rewrite the append-only file in the background to avoid an indefinite growth of the journal.
[src:keydb/redis] Journaling was introduced in version 1.1 and is generally considered the safer approach.
[src:keydb/redis] By default, Redis writes data to a file system at least every two seconds, with more or less robust options available if needed.
[src:keydb/redis] In the case of a complete system failure on default settings, only a few seconds of data will be lost.
[src:keydb/redis] Redis supports master–replica replication.
[src:keydb/redis] Data from any Redis server can replicate to any number of replicas.
[src:keydb/redis] A replica may be a master to another replica.
[src:keydb/redis] This allows Redis to implement a single-rooted replication tree.
[src:keydb/redis] Redis replicas can be configured to accept writes, permitting intentional and unintentional inconsistency between instances.
[src:keydb/redis] The publish–subscribe feature is fully implemented, so a client of a replica may subscribe to a channel and receive a full feed of messages published to the master, anywhere up the replication tree.
[src:keydb/redis] Replication is useful for read (but not write) scalability or data redundancy.
[src:keydb/redis] When the durability of data is not needed, the in-memory nature of Redis allows it to perform well compared to database systems that write every change to disk before considering a transaction committed.
[src:keydb/redis] Redis operates as a single process and is single-threaded or double-threaded when it rewrites the AOF (append-only file).
[src:keydb/redis] Thus, a single Redis instance cannot use parallel execution of tasks such as stored procedures.
[src:keydb/redis] Redis introduced clustering in April 2015 with the release of version 3.0.
[src:keydb/redis] The cluster specification implements a subset of Redis commands: all single-key commands are available, multi-key operations (commands related to unions and intersections) are restricted to keys belonging to the same node, and commands related to database selection operations are unavailable.
[src:keydb/redis] A Redis cluster can scale up to 1,000 nodes, achieve "acceptable" write safety and to continue operations when some nodes fail.
[src:keydb/redis] Redis has been used by Adobe, Airbnb, Amazon, Hulu, OpenAI, Salesforce, Shopify, Tinder, Twitter, and Yahoo.
[src:keydb/redis] Typical use cases of Redis are session caching, full page cache, message queue applications, leaderboards and counting among others.
[src:keydb/redis] The publish–subscribe messaging paradigm allows real-time communication between servers.
[src:keydb/redis] Amazon Web Services offers a managed Redis service called ElastiCache for Redis, Google offers a managed Redis service called Cloud Memorystore, Microsoft offers Azure Cache for Redis in Azure, and Alibaba offers ApsaraDB for Redis in Alibaba Cloud.
[src:keydb/redis] Redis is interfaced with by various libraries.
[src:keydb/redis] For example, POCO C++ Libraries supports interfacing with Redis through its `Poco::Redis` library.
